Introduction¶

In this project, I will explore Loan dataset from Prosper, which contains 113,937 rows and 81 columns. I will pick some of the variables that are related to Default to analyze. Firstly, some data wrangling and cleaning, and then on to EDA with different types of charts to explore relationships between/among variables, and hopefully get significant results from my research.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 entries in the dataset with 81 features. We have numeric variables, categorical variables, boolean and date. Variables like ProsperRating (Alpha) and IncomeRange can be ordered factor variables with the following levels:

ProsperRating (Alpha): AA, A, B, C, D, E, HR (best to worth)

IncomeRange: Not employed, \$0, \\$1-\$24,999, \\$25,000-\$49,999, \\$50,000-\$74,999, \\$75,000-\$99,999, \\$100,000+

Lot of null values found in some variables, such as variables prosperrating and prosperscore, which I'll need to take care of later.

Some variables are not needed for my research and will have to be truncated, such as listingkey, listingnumber, of other identifiers.

What is the main factor of interest in your dataset?¶

My point of interest is finding out what factors are most suitable for knowing whether a loan would fail or not, which is the LoanStatus variable.

What other factors do you think will help support your investigation into your main factor?¶

I expect that variables related to borrowers' personal situation would have effect on default, such as EmploymentStatus, CreditScoreRangeLower/Upper, DelinquenciesLast7Years, IncomeRange, etc. Because a borrower's financial status will have huge effect on their loan payment.

Data Assessing and Cleaning¶

Time to clean!! I will be dropping the columns I won't need for the research, and then handle the null values after which, I will take care of the float and int variables.

In [6]:
# Start by creating a copy of the original dataset. We use that for the analysis
loan_clean = loan.copy()
In [7]:
# Change column names to lowercase and replace space with underscore for convenience.
loan_clean.columns = map(str.lower, loan_clean.columns)
loan_clean.columns = loan_clean.columns.str.replace(' ', '_')

# Remove columns not needed for my research analysis.

My point of interest is which factors a more likely to have a strong enough relationship to provoke a default or not. Given that there are only 2 loan status: 1 & 0, where 1 = Default and 0 = No default, but the value counts have more than 2 states, I will assume all past due loans to default and ignore loan status = cancelled, finalpaymentinprogess or current for the purpose of my analysis. I will then encode all past dues as 1 and completed as 0 .

There is a very little difference between default rate and home owner

Conclusion¶

I have explored the correlation between Default and some other variables of interest, after univariate, bivariate, and multivarite analysis,I've found out that loan defaults are tied with certain factors such as borrower rate, income range, credit score, state, and debt to income ratio.
